<paragraph blockId="6.[151,579,1031,1092]" box="[151,574,1066,1092]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,243,1066,1092]" captionStart="PLATE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,238,1841,1865]" captionTargetBox="[244,1318,207,1814]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[240,1326,194,1814]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="PLATE 2 (isthmia and granadensis). 1,2. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 3,4. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 5,6. Brassolis granadensis Paralectotype female, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis granadensis Lectotype male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 9,10. Brassolis isthmia daisye Holotype female, COLOMBIA: Chicorral, BMNH. 11,12. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 13,14. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Holotype female, ECUADOR: Paramba, BMNH. 15,16. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, BMNH" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125057" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125057/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Plate 2</figureCitation>
, figs. 5–8; 
<figureCitation box="[374,454,1066,1092]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,238,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-116@9.[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="PLATE 3 (details). 1,2. Brassolis granadensis female, COLOMBIA: Otanche, JFL. 3. Brassolis granadensis male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4,5. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 6. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype female, COLOMBIA: Chaparral, ICNO. 9. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 10,11. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype female, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, CRB. 12. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Balzapamba (Paralectotype male of Brassolis granadensis), BMNH. 13. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 14. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 15. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125059/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Plate 3</figureCitation>
figs. 1–3)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1146,2015]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">
In the original description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1902" box="[496,672,1147,1172]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis box="[496,672,1147,1172]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">B. granadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the type series consisted of 
<specimenCount box="[1012,1103,1146,1172]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" type="male">4 males</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[1162,1264,1146,1172]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" type="female">1 female</specimenCount>
from ‘Colombien (?Muzo)’ and 
<specimenCount box="[378,469,1186,1212]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" type="male">3 males</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[528,641,1186,1212]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" type="female">2 females</specimenCount>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[715,812,1186,1212]" name="Ecuador" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(Balzapamba) caught by Haensch. In the Rothschild Collection in the BMNH there is a male with a round red ‘Type’ label, a rectangular red ‘Typus’ label, a white, rectangular, printed label ‘ 
<collectingCountry box="[455,578,1266,1292]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, R. 
<collectingRegion box="[624,754,1266,1292]" country="Colombia" name="Magdalena" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Magdalena</collectingRegion>
s e.c. Stichel’, and a handwritten ‘ 
<taxonomicName authority="Stich." authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1902" box="[1161,1419,1266,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis box="[1161,1344,1267,1292]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Br. granadensis</emphasis>
Stich.
</taxonomicName>
’. This, which corresponds with the figured specimen, has been designated 
<typeStatus box="[1003,1114,1306,1332]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">lectotype</typeStatus>
. At first sight, the Ecuadorian specimens of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1902" box="[399,542,1347,1372]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis box="[399,542,1347,1372]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">granadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
type series do not appear to be in the BMNH. However, within the series of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1903" box="[151,466,1387,1412]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="sophorae" subSpecies="ardens">
<emphasis box="[151,466,1387,1412]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Brassolis sophorae ardens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Rothschild Collection are 
<specimenCount box="[864,958,1386,1412]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" type="male">2 males</specimenCount>
, similar to 
<typeStatus box="[1094,1201,1386,1412]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">lectotype</typeStatus>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1902" box="[1210,1353,1387,1412]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis box="[1210,1353,1387,1412]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">granadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<specimenCount pageId="6" pageNumber="53" type="female">1 female</specimenCount>
(
<figureCitation box="[247,333,1426,1452]" captionStart="PLATE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,238,1841,1865]" captionTargetBox="[244,1318,207,1814]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[240,1326,194,1814]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="PLATE 2 (isthmia and granadensis). 1,2. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 3,4. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 5,6. Brassolis granadensis Paralectotype female, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis granadensis Lectotype male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 9,10. Brassolis isthmia daisye Holotype female, COLOMBIA: Chicorral, BMNH. 11,12. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 13,14. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Holotype female, ECUADOR: Paramba, BMNH. 15,16. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, BMNH" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125057" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125057/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Plate 2</figureCitation>
, figs.13&amp;14) from Balzapamba bearing Stichel’s characteristic red ‘typus’ label. As no mention of Balzapamba was made in the original description of 
<emphasis box="[863,942,1467,1492]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">ardens</emphasis>
, it would appear that these 
<specimenCount box="[1271,1362,1466,1492]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" type="male">2 males</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount pageId="6" pageNumber="53" type="female">1 female</specimenCount>
are not part of the type series of 
<emphasis box="[628,706,1507,1532]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">ardens</emphasis>
, but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1902" box="[768,911,1507,1532]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis box="[768,911,1507,1532]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">granadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. I believe that these 
<specimenCount box="[1159,1351,1506,1532]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" type="generic">three specimens</specimenCount>
, which match other specimens from west of the Andes in 
<collectingCountry box="[742,841,1546,1572]" name="Ecuador" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and differ significantly from 
<emphasis box="[1194,1273,1547,1572]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">ardens</emphasis>
which occurs east of the Andes, are some of the Ecuadorian types of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1902" box="[816,959,1587,1612]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis box="[816,959,1587,1612]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">granadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, although the Colombian and Ecuadorian specimens are similar, there are some consistent small, but significant, differences and I believe that there is a mixed type series and that two taxa are involved: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1902" box="[895,1038,1667,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis box="[895,1038,1667,1692]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">granadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1095,1327,1667,1692]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[1095,1181,1667,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isthmia">isthmia</taxonomicName>
wallengreni
</emphasis>
ssp. nov. As 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1902" box="[195,338,1707,1732]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis box="[195,338,1707,1732]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">granadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is partially sympatric in the Magdalena Valley with an undescribed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[1181,1267,1707,1732]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isthmia">
<emphasis box="[1181,1267,1707,1732]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">isthmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxon, herein named 
<emphasis box="[236,311,1747,1772]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">daisye</emphasis>
ssp. nov., I am re-instating 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1902" box="[636,779,1747,1772]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis box="[636,779,1747,1772]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">granadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1146,2015]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1436,152,338]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="54" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1902" box="[198,375,1787,1812]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis box="[198,375,1787,1812]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">B. granadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most readily identified by the female. Where the forewing band approaches the costal margin, the outer margin of the band is elongated into a flame-like structure (most evident from below—see 
<figureCitation box="[151,233,1866,1892]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,238,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-116@9.[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="PLATE 3 (details). 1,2. Brassolis granadensis female, COLOMBIA: Otanche, JFL. 3. Brassolis granadensis male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4,5. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 6. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype female, COLOMBIA: Chaparral, ICNO. 9. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 10,11. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype female, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, CRB. 12. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Balzapamba (Paralectotype male of Brassolis granadensis), BMNH. 13. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 14. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 15. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125059/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, fig. 1). In the male, the forewing band extends a short distance (
<quantity box="[998,1097,1866,1892]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3 mm</quantity>
) beyond the distal margin of the cell (
<figureCitation box="[250,333,1906,1932]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,238,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-116@9.[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="PLATE 3 (details). 1,2. Brassolis granadensis female, COLOMBIA: Otanche, JFL. 3. Brassolis granadensis male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4,5. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 6. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype female, COLOMBIA: Chaparral, ICNO. 9. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 10,11. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype female, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, CRB. 12. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Balzapamba (Paralectotype male of Brassolis granadensis), BMNH. 13. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 14. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 15. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125059/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, fig. 3), a feature that it shares with nominate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[866,952,1907,1932]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isthmia">
<emphasis box="[866,952,1907,1932]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">isthmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1007,1111,1907,1932]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">i. daisye,</emphasis>
but not with 
<emphasis box="[1265,1426,1907,1932]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">i. wallengreni</emphasis>
) (
<figureCitation box="[159,244,1946,1972]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,238,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-116@9.[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="PLATE 3 (details). 1,2. Brassolis granadensis female, COLOMBIA: Otanche, JFL. 3. Brassolis granadensis male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4,5. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 6. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype female, COLOMBIA: Chaparral, ICNO. 9. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 10,11. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype female, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, CRB. 12. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Balzapamba (Paralectotype male of Brassolis granadensis), BMNH. 13. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 14. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 15. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125059/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, fig. 12). Additionally, the forewing band in space Cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[892,900,1963,1977]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">1</subScript>
-Cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[945,953,1963,1977]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="53">2</subScript>
extends right up to the cell (
